# Question 6: Describe doubly linked list with structure. Write detailed algorithms for insertion and deletion at different positions. Compare singly, circular, and doubly linked lists based on memory and operations.

## Definition of Doubly Linked List
A doubly linked list is a linked list in which each node contains:

- Previous pointer  
- Data  
- Next pointer  

---

## Structure of Doubly Linked List

struct node {
   struct node *prev;
   int data;
   struct node *next;
};

---

## Diagram of Doubly Linked List

NULL ← 10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 → NULL

---

## Insertion at Beginning
1. Create a new node  
2. Enter data  
3. Link new node to first node  
4. Update first node pointer  

---

## Insertion at Middle
1. Find the position  
2. Create new node  
3. Adjust previous and next links  

---

## Insertion at End
1. Move to last node  
2. Create new node  
3. Link last node with new node  

---

## Deletion at Beginning
1. Remove first node  
2. Update head pointer  

---

## Deletion at Middle
1. Find the node  
2. Adjust links  
3. Delete the node  

---

## Deletion at End
1. Move to last node  
2. Delete last node  

---

## Comparison of Linked Lists

| Feature | Singly Linked List | Circular Linked List | Doubly Linked List |
|----------|--------------------|----------------------|--------------------|
| Memory | Less | Less | More |
| Traversal | One direction | Circular | Two directions |
| Insertion | Easy | Moderate | Easy |
| Deletion | Moderate | Moderate | Easy |

---

## Applications of Doubly Linked List
- Browser history  
- Undo/Redo operations  
- Music playlists  

---

## Conclusion
Doubly linked lists allow traversal in both directions and make insertion/deletion easier.
